tags: ["PYQ", "FMGE Jul 2025"],
text: "Which among the following organism is the cause of necrotizing fasciitis?",
options: [{"id": "A", "text": "Streptococcus pneumoniae", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "B", "text": "Streptococcus pyogenes", "is_correct": true}, {"id": "C", "text": "Clostridium perfringens", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "D", "text": "Clostridium tetani", "is_correct": false}],
explanation: "Necrotizing fasciitis is a rapidly progressive, life-threatening soft tissue infection most commonly caused by Group A \u03b2-hemolytic Streptococcus.<br><br>\u00b7\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Type II (monomicrobial) necrotizing fasciitis \u2192 classically due to Streptococcus pyogenes\n\u00b7\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Produces exotoxins (streptococcal pyrogenic exotoxins) \u2192 tissue destruction, systemic toxicity, toxic shock<br><br>\u00b7\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0Clinical features:\no\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Severe pain out of proportion to findings\no\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Rapid spread along fascial planes\no\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Skin necrosis, bullae, crepitus (late)\no\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Systemic toxicity (fever, shock)<br><br>Why not others:\n\u00b7\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Streptococcus pneumoniae \u2192 pneumonia, meningitis\n\u00b7\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Clostridium perfringens \u2192 gas gangrene (myonecrosis), not classic necrotizing fasciitis\n\u00b7\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Clostridium tetani \u2192 tetanus (neurotoxin-mediated disease)",
images: []
