id: "061d67afdb09beab",
category: "Microbiology",
subcategory: "01-bacteriology",
tags: ["ZVRecommended", "PYQ", "NEET PG 2023"],
text: "A young male came to the hospital with a clean-cut wound without any bleeding. The patient received a full course of tetanus vaccination 10 years ago. What is the best management for this patient?",
options: [{"id": "A", "text": "Human tetanus immunoglobulin and full course of vaccine", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "B", "text": "Human tetanus immunoglobulin only", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "C", "text": "Single-dose tetanus toxoid", "is_correct": true}, {"id": "D", "text": "Full course tetanus toxoid", "is_correct": false}],
explanation: "A clean-cut wound is classified as a clean, minor wound with low risk of tetanus.\nIn an individual who has completed the full primary tetanus immunization, a booster dose of tetanus toxoid is recommended if more than 10 years have elapsed since the last dose.\nHuman tetanus immunoglobulin is not required for clean wounds in adequately immunized individuals, and restarting the full course is unnecessary.<br><br><img src=\"https://corebtr-assets-production.s3.ap-south-1.amazonaws.com/question_explanation/cc8a3a1f-6c9e-4144-8419-8531f8157577.png\" alt=\"Uploaded Image\"><br><br><br>",
